  "prompt": "Why do mosquitoes come out in the evening time?",
  "response": "Mosquitoes are most active in the evening (dusk) and early morning (dawn) for a few key reasons:\n\n*   **Avoiding the Heat of the Day:** Mosquitoes are small and can easily dehydrate in the hot sun. Evening and early morning are cooler and more humid, providing a more favorable environment for them to fly and search for a blood meal without drying out.\n\n*   **Reduced Wind:** Wind can make it difficult for mosquitoes to fly. Wind speeds tend to be lower in the evening and early morning, making it easier for them to navigate and locate hosts.\n\n*   **Light Sensitivity:** Some mosquito species are sensitive to bright light. The lower light levels of dusk and dawn provide a more comfortable environment for them to be active.\n\n*   **Host Availability:** For some mosquito species, their preferred hosts (e.g., humans, animals) may be more active outdoors during the evening, making it a convenient time for the mosquitoes to find a blood meal.",
